      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To check for this \"corrosive tide\" without having to start chipping away at the foundation like a clumsy, oversized badger, engineers use a whole arsenal of non-destructive testing (NDT) methods. These techniques are like having a highly trained, very cautious scout looking for trouble without setting off the entire horde of goblins.\n\nOne common method is using half-cell potential mapping, which essentially measures the electrical potential difference between the steel and the surrounding concrete. If the potential drops below a certain threshold, it's a big red flag, suggesting the steel is actively corroding. Another technique involves using ground-penetrating radar (GPR), which sends electromagnetic waves into the structure to map out the rebar's location and detect changes in density or moisture content around it.\n\nThese methods allow engineers to get a good idea of the internal health, spotting areas where the moisture ingress is starting to turn the steel into a grumpy, expanding rust-goblin. Sometimes, they might use ultrasonic pulse velocity tests to check the overall integrity of the concrete itself, making sure it hasn't become too porous to let the corrosive sludge seep in.",
